  "notes": [
    "Additional recommended courses prior to transfer: Two additional semesters of calculus based physics with lab. UCLA's Chem 153A and/or 153L are upper-division courses that satisfy major requirements but are NOT required for admission. After transferring, students must petition for transfer credit and should contact the academic advisor for their major for additional support and details about this process.",
    "The Chemistry/Materials Science major is designed for students who are interested in chemistry with an emphasis on material properties and provides students the opportunity to gain expertise in both chemistry and the science and engineering in materials such as semiconductors, photonic materials, polymers, biomaterials, ceramics, and nano-scale structures. Students explore the reactivity of such materials in different environments and gain understanding of how composition affects properties. Listed below are the lower division preparation courses for the major. To be considered for admission to this major, you must complete the following courses by the end of spring before transfer: One year of General Chemistry with Lab, One and a half years of Calculus through Multivariable, One course in Linear Algebra, One course in Organic Chemistry with Lab, One course in Calculus Based Physics (for Engineering majors) with Lab. All courses must be taken for a letter grade. For more information regarding this major and UCLA's selection process, visit https:// chemistry.ucla.edu and https:// admission.ucla.edu. PLEASE NOTE: the community college courses listed below have been approved to satisfy the preparation requirements for this major at UCLA, but they may not be exact equivalents of the UCLA courses listed.",
    "The AP Scores listed below may be used to satisfy the major prep: A score of 4 or higher on the AP Chemistry exam can be used in place of CHEM 20A ONLY. A score of 5 on the AP Calculus AB exam will satisfy MATH 31A. A score of 4 on the AP Calculus BC exam will satisfy MATH 31A. A score of 5 on the AP Calculus BC exam will satisfy MATH 31A and 31B. The IB Exam Scores listed below may be used to satisfy the major prep: A score of 6 or higher on the IB HL Chemistry exam can be used in place of CHEM 20A ONLY. A score of 6 or higher on the IB HL Math Analysis & Approaches exam will satisfy MATH 31A."
  ]
